description: CodeBoarding is an AI‑assisted documentation tool that follows a "Static Analysis as Ground Truth" philosophy. It orchestrates a pipeline that starts with deterministic code scanning via LSP to build a comprehensive call graph, clusters this graph into logical topologies, and then uses a multi‑agent AI layer to assign responsibilities and generate architectural narratives. A stateful incremental engine leverages Git diffing and DuckDB‑backed caching to efficiently handle large repositories, finally producing interactive HTML and Markdown documentation.

components.name: Core Orchestration & CLI
components.description: The central coordinator managing the analysis lifecycle, environment setup, and high-level workflow. It handles repository cloning, configuration loading, and sequences the transition from raw code to structured documentation. It also manages the tool registry for LSP binaries and plugin loading.

components.name: Workflow Orchestrator
components.description: The primary controller that sequences the analysis pipeline. It manages the entry point logic, handles high‑level job state via DuckDB, and coordinates the generation of final outputs (JSON and Mermaid diagrams). It bridges the gap between user configuration and the specialized analysis engines.

components.name: Environment & Tool Registry
components.description: Manages the discovery and lifecycle of internal plugins and external LSP tools. It maintains a central registry of analysis providers and ensures that language‑specific binaries (e.g., for Python, Java, or Go) are correctly provisioned. It also provides the caching infrastructure to ensure analysis results are persisted and reused.

components.name: Repository & Workspace Manager
components.description: Handles all filesystem and Git‑level operations required to prepare the codebase. This includes cloning repositories, identifying code deltas (ChangeImpact) for incremental workflows, and managing the local workspace where analysis artifacts are stored.

components.name: AI Agent Infrastructure
components.description: The agentic reasoning layer that interprets static analysis data. It manages LLM configurations, prompt construction via specialized factories, and ensures that LLM responses conform to the expected architectural schemas.

components.name: Monitoring & Health Diagnostics
components.description: Provides observability and quality assurance for both the analysis process and the target codebase. It tracks LLM token usage and costs while running diagnostic checks (like unused code detection) to validate the health of the analyzed project.

components.name: Static Analysis & LSP Engine
components.description: Responsible for the deterministic extraction of code structure and topological organization. It manages LSP binaries for multiple languages and executes scans to produce call graphs and symbol tables. It applies adaptive clustering algorithms to group related code elements into logical components.

components.name: Environment Discovery & Registry
components.description: Acts as the pre‑analysis phase, identifying programming languages and detecting build system configurations (e.g., Maven, Gradle) to provide metadata such as classpaths and server parameters required for LSP initialization.

components.name: LSP Orchestration & Execution
components.description: Central execution engine that manages the lifecycle of various LSP binaries, coordinating the ProjectScanner to run language‑specific requests (call hierarchies, symbol flattening) across ecosystems like TypeScript and Java, abstracting LSP complexities into a unified data‑extraction interface.

components.name: Topological Analysis & Clustering
components.description: Post‑analysis phase that processes raw symbol and call data to build a directed call graph and applies adaptive clustering (balancing and merging) to organize code elements into high‑level logical components based on topological relationships, preparing data for AI interpretation.

components_relations.relation: Provides language metadata and build configurations (classpaths, server params) to initialize LSP clients.
Feeds extracted symbol tables and call hierarchy data into the graph engine for structural organization.

components.name: Agentic Interpretation Layer
components.description: An AI-driven reasoning engine that interprets clustered graph data. It uses specialized agents (Abstraction, Details, Meta) to assign responsibilities to components, identify patterns, and generate descriptive narratives based on the structural ground truth provided by the static analysis.

components.name: Agent Reasoning Core
components.description: The central execution engine that manages the lifecycle of AI reasoning tasks. It coordinates the specialized AbstractionAgent (for high‑level structure) and DetailsAgent (for deep‑dives), implementing a validation‑driven loop that handles retries and ensures the LLM's output aligns with the project's architectural goals.

components.name: Instruction Synthesis System
components.description: A decoupled prompt engineering layer that uses the Factory pattern to generate model‑specific instructions. It abstracts the complexity of different LLM providers (Claude, GPT, Gemini) by providing standardized templates for system personas, task expansion, and validation feedback.

components.name: Structural Ground Truth Tools
components.description: A collection of deterministic analysis tools that provide agents with read‑only access to the repository's structure. These tools bridge the gap between the LLM and the static analysis engine, allowing agents to query CFGs, read source code, and analyze package dependencies to ground their reasoning in factual evidence.

components.name: Graph Reconciliation Logic
components.description: A specialized logic layer, primarily implemented via mixins, that reconciles unstructured AI narratives with deterministic graph clusters. It handles the mapping of logical component names to physical node IDs and validates that the agent's interpretation covers the necessary parts of the call graph.

components.name: Semantic Output Schemas
components.description: Defines the structured data contracts (Pydantic models) that serve as the formal vocabulary for the interpretation layer. These schemas ensure that LLM responses are parsed into type‑safe objects representing architectural insights, component relationships, and file classifications.

components.name: Incremental Analysis & State Manager
components.description: Manages system statefulness and performance. It uses Git diffing to detect changes and a caching layer to store analysis results and LLM responses, allowing for incremental updates of large repositories by only re-analyzing modified sections.

components.name: Change Detection Engine
components.description: Acts as the primary trigger for the incremental workflow by utilizing Git diffing to identify added, modified, deleted, or renamed files. It encapsulates the logic for determining the "dirty" scope of the repository and produces a ChangeSet that distinguishes between structural changes and content-only updates.

components.name: Static Analysis Cache Manager
components.description: Manages the lifecycle and persistence of deterministic structural data, such as Call Flow Graphs (CFG) and class hierarchies. It handles the serialization of analysis results to disk and provides the data models used to represent the "Ground Truth" extracted by LSP tools, ensuring structural fragments can be merged into the global state.

components.name: LLM & Metadata Cache
components.description: A performance-focused caching layer that fingerprints files and hashes LLM prompts to create unique signatures. It stores AI responses and "watch states" in a SQLite-backed store, acting as a buffer that allows the system to skip redundant AI interpretation for code context that has not changed.

components.name: Incremental Update Orchestrator
components.description: The central logic hub that coordinates the patching of the global analysis state. It utilizes granular IO utilities to read and write individual analysis fragments (sub-analyses) and merges new deltas into the unified project JSON. It ensures that the state of the incremental analysis is always synchronized with the physical file changes.

components.name: Multi-Format Output Generation
components.description: Transforms the validated architectural model into user-facing formats. It generates Mermaid.js diagrams, Markdown documentation, and interactive HTML reports using Cytoscape.js for visualization.

components.name: Architectural Model Parser
components.description: The foundational data layer that defines core schemas (UnifiedAnalysisJson, ComponentJson) and parses architectural analysis results into a consistent intermediate representation for downstream generators.

components.name: Static Documentation Generator
components.description: Transforms the architectural model into text‑heavy documentation formats, generating Mermaid.js syntax and embedding it into Markdown, MDX, or RST templates to keep documentation integrated with the source repository.

components.name: Interactive Visualization Generator
components.description: Produces dynamic, browser‑based architectural reports by mapping analysis data to Cytoscape.js JSON and populating HTML templates, also handling GitHub Action orchestration for automated CI/CD documentation updates.

components.name: Output Orchestrator
components.description: High‑level control layer for local execution; validates CLI arguments, manages repository state, and coordinates static and interactive generators based on user configuration.

components.name: Static Health Diagnostics
components.description: A code quality sub-system that leverages LSP diagnostics and static analysis to identify health issues such as circular dependencies, god classes, and unused code. It provides supplementary data for the final health report.

components.name: Diagnostic Orchestrator
components.description: Manages the end-to-end lifecycle of a health analysis run, including language discovery, check selection based on the environment, and final result aggregation.

components.name: LSP Diagnostic Engine
components.description: Leverages Language Server Protocol (LSP) data to identify unused code, imports, and variables. It handles the collection of raw diagnostics and their transformation into categorized health issues.

components.name: Structural Integrity Analyzers
components.description: A suite of static analysis tools that evaluate architectural patterns, detecting "God Classes," deep inheritance hierarchies, and circular dependencies.

components.name: Extensibility Bridge
components.description: Facilitates the integration of third-party health checks via the project's registry system, ensuring the subsystem can be extended without modifying the core engine.

components.name: Health Modeling & Scoring
components.description: Defines the standardized data structures for health findings and implements the mathematical logic to translate raw diagnostic counts into normalized health scores.
